      "published": "2018-04-11T20:54:00.000+03:00",
      "title": "Cash crunch not to hit farm input scheme, says TS govt.",
      "text": "April 11, 2018 23:24   23:24 IST more-in Telangana RBI assures enough cash supply for Rythu Bandhu scheme \nThe Telangana government has allayed fears that the present cash crunch in banks may adversely impact the Crop Investment Support Scheme after the Finance Department got a categorical assurance from the Reserve Bank of India officials that ₹6,000 crore cash required for the scheme will be released to the banks soon. \nSources told The Hindu on Wednesday that the government issued the Budget Release Order for ₹ 6,000 crore to the Agriculture Department on Tuesday, of which ₹ 2,000 crore was released to the department on Wednesday. The department in turn will release the amount to various banks to allow the farmers encash their bearer cheques under the Crop Investment Support scheme as and when they require it. The government decided to give ₹ 4,000 per acre to the farmers under the scheme for Kharif and and an equal amount for Rabi season. The scheme would cost the government about ₹ 12,000 crore in a year. \nFirst tranche \nThe government will release another ₹ 2,000 crore to the Agriculture Department by month-end. “The government is fully geared to distribute the cheques to the farmers. The first tranche of 16 lakh cheques has been received in Hyderabad and being checked by officials. The cheques will be despatched to the mandals in a couple of days. We are ready with logistics and infrastructure to roll out the scheme to help the farmers buy inputs required for their crops in time,” sources said. \nThe State earns about ₹10,000 crore revenue a month and it is not difficult for it to allocate the required amount to the agriculture department for the crop investment support scheme. The Finance Department can also raise market loans to augment the funds, sources said. \nHighly placed sources also confirmed that the RBI has agreed to the State’s request to increase the money supply to the State. It would release ₹ 6,000 crore to the banks over a period of one month to one-and-a half month. \nThe distribution of cheques to farmers is expected to start in the third week of April though no date has been announced so far. The date will be announced soon by the Chief Minister, sources added. \nIncentives to banks \nMeanwhile, the government is considering to request the banks to give priority in releasing cash to farmers who present the bearer cheques under the crop investment support scheme. There will be incentives to those banks which facilitate farmers to encash their cheques, they said. \nCommenting on the cash crunch in the banks, government sources said that it was apparent that people who had withdrawn money were not depositing the cash back for various reasons. But government could not force people to deposit the cash into the banks. \n“For some reason, either due to unknown fears, recent scams in public sector and private banks, people are opting to keep cash with them rather than in the banks for the fear that they may not be able to withdraw cash when they need it,” they explained.",
