      "text": "Our Bureau T+ T- (From left); Alokananda Roy,Chairman West Bengal State Commission for Women, C S Ghosh Chairman & MD, Bandhan Bank & Craig L Hall, US Consul General, Kolkata at ‘Development Day’ celebration of Bandhan Konnagar. - Debasish Bhaduri NGO set to receive World Bank funding support for the same Kolkata, April 11 \nBandhan-Konnagar, a non-profit organisation of the Bandhan group, is looking to provide financial support to close to 3 lakh underprivileged families under its targeting hardcore poor (THP) programme in the next five years. \nAccording to Chandra Shekhar Ghosh, Founder & Mentor, Bandhan-Konnagar, the NGO is set to receive World Bank funding support for the same. As many as 70,000 families have benefited under the THP programme till so far. \n“The World Bank wants us to scale up the THP programme in the states of Rajasthan, Bihar, Jharkhand and Odisha. We hope to be able to bring close to 3 lakh underprivileged families under this programme in the next five years,” Ghosh told newspersons on the sidelines of the ‘Development Day’ celebration of Bandhan-Konnagar here on Wednesday. \nTHP programme has been implemented in Assam, West Bengal, Jharkhand, Bihar, Odisha, Telangana, Madhya Pradesh, Rajasthan and Tripura. State governments of Rajasthan and Jharkhand have tied up with Bandhan-Konnagar, providing them financial support for the implementation of the programme in certain districts of the State, he said. \nThe NGO spends close to Rs 25,000-30,000 per family on an average during the 24-months programme. Apart from World Bank funding support, Bandhan Bank has earmarked close to 2 per cent of its CSR spend on the programme. It also receives funding support from corporates like ITC, HDFC and Indigo, among others. \nUnder the 24-months THP programme, the NGO identifies hardcore poor families who have not had access to traditional finance initiatives and provides them with a productive livelihood asset such as poultry, handicrafts, sew